'''Josue Ortega''' is a lecturer in economics at the [[University of Essex]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.essex.ac.uk/people/ORTEG58802/josue-alberto-ortega-sandoval|title=Ortega's website at the University of Essex|last=|first=|date=July 2, 2018|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> He is the author of a controversial article that suggests that the emergence of online dating has caused an increase in the number of interracial marriages in the US.<ref>{{Cite arxiv|last=Ortega|first=Josue|last2=Hergovich|first2=Philipp|date=2017-09-29|title=The Strength of Absent Ties: Social Integration via Online Dating|eprint=1709.10478|class=physics.soc-ph}}</ref> Ortega's findings have been covered by international media, including ''[[Forbes]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/janetwburns/2017/10/25/theres-now-evidence-that-online-dating-causes-stronger-more-diverse-relationships/#394ee63158bd|title=There's Now Evidence That Online Dating Causes Stronger, More Diverse Marriages|last=Burns|first=Janet|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-07-02|language=en}}</ref> ''[[the Times]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/online-dating-is-leading-to-more-mixed-marriages-ksvgjg3tp|title=Online dating is leading to more mixed marriages|last=Editor|first=Greg Hurst, Social Affairs|date=2017-10-17|work=The Times|access-date=2018-07-02|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> ''[[New Scientist]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/2150609-online-dating-may-be-breaking-down-societys-racial-divisions/|title=Online dating may be breaking down society’s racial divisions|work=New Scientist|access-date=2018-07-02|language=en-US}}</ref> ''[[Business Insider]]''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.de/happy-marriage-online-dating-2017-10?r=UK&IR=T|title=Scientists think relationships that start online may have a huge advantage over relationships that start in real life|work=Business Insider Deutschland|access-date=2018-07-02|language=de}}</ref> and the ''[[MIT Technology Review]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/609091/first-evidence-that-online-dating-is-changing-the-nature-of-society/|title=The way strangers meet via dating websites is changing society in unexpected ways, say researchers|last=arXiv|first=Emerging Technology from the|work=MIT Technology Review|access-date=2018-07-02|language=en}}</ref> Ortega has been interviewed by ''[[Thinking Allowed]]'' at [[BBC Radio 4]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b09wt181|title=Dating at university, Online dating, Thinking Allowed - BBC Radio 4|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-07-02}}</ref>
Ortega obtained his PhD at the [[University of Glasgow]] under the supervision of Professor [[Hervé Moulin]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gla.ac.uk/schools/business/staff/hervemoulin/#/supervision|title=Professor Herve Moulin's website.|last=|first=|date=July 2, 2018|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> He received the Catherine Richards prize by the UK [[Institute for Mathematics and its Applications]] in 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ima.org.uk/3984/playing-tennis-without-envy/|title=Playing Tennis without Envy - IMA|date=2016-12-01|work=IMA|access-date=2018-07-02|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gla.ac.uk/schools/business/newsandevents/newsarchive/2016/headline_486584_en.html|title=University of Glasgow - Schools - Adam Smith Business School - News and events - News archive - 2016 - PhD student awarded IMA Catherine Richards Prize|website=www.gla.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-07-02}}</ref>
