{{about|the deities in Egyptian mythology|the concept in Gnosticism|Ogdoad (Gnosticism)}}
[[File:L'Ogdoade d'Hermopolis.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Depiction of the Ogdoad with serpent and frog heads (Roman-era relief at the [[Dendera Temple complex|Hathor temple in Dendera]]).]]
[[File:The dawn of civilization- Egypt and Chaldaea (1897) (14763536725).jpg|thumb|300px|right|Drawing of a representation of the Ogdoad in the temple of [[Philae]].<ref>"Drawn by Faucher-Gudin from a photograph by Béato. C.f. Lepsius, ''Denkm'', iv.pl.66 ''c''.", published in Maspero (1897).
The scene is collapsed from "the two extremities of a great scene at Philae, in which the Eight, divided into two groups of four, take part in the adoration of the king."</ref>]]
In [[Egyptian mythology]], the '''Ogdoad''' ({{lang-grc|ὀγδοάς}} "the Eightfold"; {{lang-egy|ḫmnyw}}, a plural [[Afroasiatic languages#Nisba|nisba]] of {{lang|egy|ḫmnw}} "eight") were eight [[primordial deities]] worshipped in [[Hermopolis]].

References to the Ogdoad date to the [[Old Kingdom of Egypt]], and even at the time of composition of the [[Pyramid Texts]] towards the end of the Old Kingdom, they appear to have been antiquated and mostly forgotten by everyone except religious experts. They are frequently mentioned in the [[Coffin Texts]] of the [[Middle Kingdom of Egypt|Middle Kingdom]]. The oldest known pictorial representations of the group do not predate the time of [[Seti I]] ([[New Kingdom of Egypt|New Kingdom]], 13th century BC), when the group appears to be rediscovered by the theologians of [[Hermopolis]] for the purposes of a more elaborate creation account.<ref>Sethe (1929), 35ff, 65f.</ref>

Texts of the [[Late Period of ancient Egypt|Late Period]] describe them as having the heads of frogs (male) and serpents (female), and they are often depicted in this way in reliefs of the [[Ptolemaic Kingdom]].<ref>{{citation| first = Mark|last =  Smith | title = On the Primaeval Ocean |year = 2002 |page =  38 }}</ref> 

[[E. A. Wallis Budge]] (1904) compares the concept to a group of four pairs of primeval gods mentioned in the Babylonian ''[[Enûma Eliš]]'', viz. [[Abzu]] and [[Tiamat]], [[Lahmu|Lahmu and Lahamu]], [[Anshar]] and [[Kishar]], [[Anu]] and [[Enki|Nudimmud]].<ref>Budge (1902), [https://archive.org/stream/godsofegyptianso00budg#page/287/mode/2up p.  287f.]</ref>

Budge also argues that the Ogdoad is the original "company of gods" or ''[[wikt:pꜣwt|pꜣwt]] [[wikt:nṯrw|nṯrw]]'', represented by nine "axes" or "flagpoles" (the hieroglyph sign for "[[ancient Egyptian deities|god]]", <hiero>N10:t-R8*R8*R8*R8*R8*R8*R8*R8*R8</hiero>),arrived at by augmenting the original Ogdoad by the local chief deity of [[Heliopolis (ancient Egypt)|Heliopolis]], [[Atum|Tem]], by the authors of the theological system reflected in the Pyramid Texts.{{sfn|Budge|1904|p=282}}

==Names==
The eight deities were arranged in four male-female pairs (the female names being merely derivative  female forms of the male names), as follows:{{sfn|Budge|1904|p= 283}}
{|class="wikitable"
|-
|[[Nu (mythology)|Nu]]  <hiero>W24*W24*W24:N1-N35A-A40</hiero>|| [[Nut (goddess)|Nut]] <hiero>W24*W24*W24:N1-N35A X1:H8-B1</hiero> 
|-
|[[Huh (god)|Ḥeḥu]] <hiero>V28-V28-G43-A40</hiero> || [[Huh (god)|Ḥeḥut]] <hiero>V28-V28-G43-X1:H8-B1</hiero> 
|-
|[[Kek (mythology)|Kekui]] <hiero>V31:V31-y-G43-N2-A40</hiero>|| [[Kek (mythology)|Kekuit]]  <hiero>V31:V31-y-G43-N2-X1:H8-B1</hiero>
|-
|Qerḥ <hiero>W11:r-V28-D41-A40</hiero>|| Qerḥet <hiero>W11:r-V28-D41:X1*H8-B1</hiero>
|}
The names of [[Nu (mythology)|Nu and Nut]] are written with the determiners for [[sky (hieroglyph)|sky]] and [[N-water ripple (n hieroglyph)|water]], and it seems clear that they represent the primordial waters.

The fourth pair appears with varying names,  sometimes the name ''Qerḥ'' is replaced by  ''Ni, Nenu, Nut, or [[Amun]]'', and the name ''Qerḥet'' by ''Ennit, Nenuit, Nut, Nit, or [[Amunet]]''. The common meaning of ''qerḥ'' is "night", but the determinative (D41 for "to halt, stop, deny") also suggests the principle of inactivity or repose.{{sfn|Budge|1904|p=283-286}}

==Attributes==
[[Huh (god)|Ḥeḥu and Ḥeḥut]] have no readily identifiable determiners; according to a suggestion due to [[Heinrich Karl Brugsch|Brugsch]] (1885), the name is associated with a term for an undefined or [[Infinity (philosophy)|unlimited number]], ''ḥeḥ'', suggesting a concept similar to Greek ''[[Aeon|aion]]''. But from the context of a number of passages in which Ḥeḥu is mentioned, Brugsch also suggested that he may be a personification of the atmosphere between heaven and earth (c.f. ''[[Shu (Egyptian god)|Shu]]'').

The names of [[Kek (mythology)|Kekui and Kekuit]] are written with a determiner combining the  [[sky (hieroglyph)|sky hieroglyph]] with a staff or scepter used for words related to darkness and obscurity, and ''kkw'' as a regular word means "darkness", suggesting that these gods represent [[darkness|primordial darkness]], comparable to Greek [[Erebus]], but in some aspects they appear to represent day as well as night, or the change from night to day and from day to night.

The fourth pair has no consistent attributes as it appears with varying names. The common meaning of ''qerḥ'' is "night", but the determinative (D41 for "to halt, stop, deny") also suggests the principle of inactivity or repose.{{sfn|Budge|1904|p=283-286}}

There is no obvious way to allot or attribute four functions to the four pairs of gods, and it seems clear that "the ancient Egyptians themselves had no very clear idea" regarding such functions. {{sfn|Budge|1904|p= 287-288}} 
Nevertheless, there have been attempts to assign "four ontological concepts"<ref>Harco Willems (1996) - [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2fMiG2dGPpYC&pg The Coffin of Heqata: (Cairo JdE 36418) : a Case Study of Egyptian Funerary Culture of the Early Middle Kingdom] - [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2fMiG2dGPpYC&pg=PA470  p.470f] Peeters Publishers, 1996.</ref>
to the four groups.
For example, in the context of the New Kingdom,  [[Maulana Karenga|Karenga]] (2004) uses "fluidity" (for "flood, waters"),   "darkness", "unboundedness" and "invisibility" (for "repose, inactivity").<ref>[[Maulana Karenga]] (2004) - [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ams2OPbmHMUC&pg Maat, the Moral Ideal in Ancient Egypt: A Study in Classical African Ethics] - [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ams2OPbmHMUC&pg=PA177  p.177] Psychology Press, 2004 {{ISBN|0415947537}} - Volume 70 of ''[http://poj.peeters-leuven.be/content.php?url=journal&journal_code=olp Orientalia Lovaniensia analecta]''.</ref>

